  "notes": "Test data generation assumptions:\n\n1. **Physical Realism**: All values respect physical constraints:\n   - Temperatures in Kelvin (>0K, typically 200-320K for Earth)\n   - Pressures in Pascals (positive)\n   - Fractions/ratios in [0,1] (soil moisture)\n   - Wind velocities can be negative (directional)\n   - Salinity in practical salinity units (PSU, typically 30-37)\n\n2. **Array Dimensions**: \n   - 1D arrays: 1-10 elements (typical for vertical profiles)\n   - 2D arrays: 2x3 to 5x7 elements (spatial grids or time-space)\n   - Consistent dimensions within each test case\n\n3. **NetCDF Context**:\n   - Variable names follow climate/earth science conventions\n   - Time indices (nt) range from 0 to 364 (annual cycle)\n   - Dimension names follow CF conventions (lat, lon, lev, time)\n\n4. **Edge Cases**:\n   - Zero values: Valid for radiation at night\n   - Single elements: Minimum array size boundary\n   - Negative values: Valid for directional quantities (wind, heat flux)\n   - Large values: Cumulative quantities over long periods\n\n5. **File Operations**:\n   - Modes tested: 'r' (read), 'w' (write), 'a' (append implied)\n   - File descriptor states: open/closed\n   - Multi-file scenarios with posNOTonfile flag\n\n6. **Data Types**: All numeric data uses float64 precision suitable for scientific computing\n\n7. **Special Scenarios**:\n   - Time series access at specific time steps\n   - Multi-file dataset handling\n   - Dimension queries for typical climate model grids (96x144 lat-lon)\n\nAll test cases are designed to be independent and can be executed in any order."
